   "source": [
    "### 1. Data Generation and Initial Plot\\n",
    "\\n",
    "We begin by creating a synthetic dataset for monthly U.S. car sales and GDP from 2021 to 2024. The car sales data is designed to have:\\n",
    "- **Trend**: A clear upward trend over time.\\n",
    "- **Seasonality**: A peak during the summer months to simulate higher sales during that period.\\n",
    "- **Noise**: Random fluctuations to mimic real-world data.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "The initial plot shows the car sales data exhibiting both the upward trend and the summer seasonality, while the GDP data shows a steady, slower-growing trend."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2. Stationarity Test (Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test)\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**Objective**: A time series needs to be stationary for a SARIMA model to be effective. A stationary series is one whose statistical properties (like mean and variance) do not change over time. The Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test is used to check for stationarity.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**Interpretation in Our Case**:\\n",
    "- **Null Hypothesis (H0)**: The series is non-stationary (it has a unit root).\\n",
    "- **p-value**: The test on the original car sales data yields a high p-value (much greater than 0.05), so we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This confirms the series is non-stationary, as expected due to the trend and seasonality.\\n",
    "- **Differencing**: To make the series stationary, we apply seasonal differencing (`.diff(12)`), which subtracts the value from the previous year. The ADF test on the differenced data gives a p-value less than 0.05, indicating the series is now stationary."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 3. ACF and PACF Plots for Order Selection\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**Objective**: The Autocorrelation Function (ACF) and Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF) plots help us determine the order of the AR, MA, SAR, and SMA terms (p, q, P, Q).\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**Interpretation in Our Case**:\\n",
    "- **ACF Plot**: Shows the correlation of the series with its lags. We look for a \\"cut-off\\" point where the correlations drop to zero.\\n",
    "  - The significant spike at lag 1 that cuts off immediately suggests a **q=1** (MA order).\\n",
    "  - The significant spike at the seasonal lag 12 suggests a **Q=1** (Seasonal MA order).\\n",
    "- **PACF Plot**: Shows the correlation of the series with its lags, after removing the effects of the intermediate lags.\\n",
    "  - The significant spike at lag 1 that cuts off suggests a **p=1** (AR order).\\n",
    "  - The significant spike at the seasonal lag 12 suggests a **P=1** (Seasonal AR order).\\n",
    "\\n",
    "This gives us the SARIMAX order `(p,d,q)(P,D,Q)s` = `(1,0,1)(1,1,1)12`.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "### Documenting and Fixing the Lag Error\\n",
    "\\n",
    "When plotting the ACF and PACF, an error can occur if the number of specified `lags` is too large relative to the number of data points in the series. Our seasonally differenced series (`Car_Sales_Diff`) has 36 observations. A common rule of thumb is that the number of lags should not exceed half of the observations (i.e., 36 / 2 = 18). The original code used `lags=20`, which violates this rule and would cause a `ValueError`.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**The Fix:**\\n",
    "\\n",
    "We will reduce the number of lags from 20 to a more appropriate value, such as 15.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**Why This Happens from a SARIMAX Perspective:**\\n",
    "\\n",
    "The ACF and PACF plots are fundamental tools for identifying the `p` and `q` parameters of a SARIMA model. These plots show the correlation of a time series with its own past values. To get a reliable estimate of these correlations, you need a sufficient number of data points. When you request too many lags for a short series, the correlation estimates for the higher lags become statistically unreliable because they are calculated with very few overlapping data points. This is why `statsmodels` raises an error.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "By choosing a smaller number of lags, we ensure that the ACF and PACF plots are both computable and interpretable, allowing us to make a more informed decision about the model's order."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4. SARIMAX Model Summary Interpretation\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**Objective**: The model summary provides a detailed statistical overview of the fitted model, helping us assess its quality and the significance of its parameters.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "**Interpretation of Key Sections**:\\n",
    "- **Left Table (Model Overview)**:\\n",
    "  - `Dep. Variable`: The target variable, `Car_Sales`.\\n",
    "  - `Model`: `SARIMAX(1, 0, 1)x(1, 1, 1, 12)` confirms the orders we chose.\\n",
    "  - `Log Likelihood`: The higher, the better the fit. It's a measure of how well the model explains the data.\\n",
    "  - `AIC`, `BIC`, `HQIC`: Information criteria that balance model fit with complexity. Lower values are generally better.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "- **Right Table (Coefficient Estimates)**:\\n",
    "  - `coef`: The estimated coefficient for each term. For example, the `GDP` coefficient shows how much car sales are expected to change for a one-unit change in GDP.\\n",
    "  - `P>|z|`: The p-value for each coefficient. A value less than 0.05 indicates the coefficient is statistically significant.\\n",
    "    - In our case, the `GDP`, `ar.L1`, `ma.L1`, `ar.S.L12`, and `ma.S.L12` terms are all significant, suggesting they are important for the model.\\n",
    "\\n",
    "- **Bottom Table (Statistical Tests)**:\\n",
    "  - **Ljung-Box (Q)**: Tests for autocorrelation in the residuals. A p-value greater than 0.05 (Prob(Q)) suggests there is no significant autocorrelation, which is good. Our model passes this test.\\n",
    "  - **Jarque-Bera (JB)**: Tests for normality of the residuals. A p-value greater than 0.05 (Prob(JB)) suggests the residuals are normally distributed, which is an assumption of the model. Our model passes this test.\\n",
    "  - **Heteroskedasticity (H)**: Tests if the variance of the residuals is constant. A p-value greater than 0.05 suggests the variance is constant (homoskedasticity), which is good. Our model passes this test.\\n",
    "  - **Skew** and **Kurtosis**: Measures of the shape of the residual distribution. A skew near 0 and kurtosis near 3 indicate a normal distribution."
   ]
  },
